{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17516627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17516627"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:45:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12673"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12673","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12673"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.69,0.06,0.01,0.15]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5149"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5149","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5149"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12673"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20769"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"3470"},{"type":"tags","id":"3633"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"8689"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9019"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35902"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43891"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"35961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/35961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn otherwise well 22-year-old woman presents to the clinic with a one-week history of diarrhoea, abdominal cramps and bloating. She describes greasy, foul-smelling stools that occur multiple times per day. Her symptoms have not improved and they are worse after eating. She reports drinking untreated water while on a camping trip in a nearby state park two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination her blood pressure is 125/80 mmHg, heart rate 80/min, temperature 37.4\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC and respiratory rate 19/min. Her abdomen is soft and with no areas of tenderness and the rest of the examination is unremarkable. Stool microscopy is performed and demonstrates numerous cystic lesions.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate treatment?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole","Metronidazole","Paromomycin","Penicillin","Albendazole"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient almost certainly has some form of infectious diarrhoea. Based on her symptoms, history, and stool test results, it is likely that she has contracted Giardiasis, which is caused by the Giardia intestinalis parasite. Giardia is commonly spread through contaminated water or food, and symptoms typically include diarrhoea, abdominal cramps, bloating, and greasy, foul-smelling stools. The characteristic microscopic appearance of the cysts are ovoid to ellipsoid in shape. Trophozoites may be apparent, and these are pear-shaped with two nuclei and flagella. Several stool samples may need to be examined to identify this parasite. If giardiasis is suspected as being the underlying cause of a patient\u0027s illness and stool microscopy has been inconclusive, the PCR and ELISA testing should be considered.  These tests show greater sensitivity and specificity than stool microscopy. Treatment typically involves a course of antibiotics, such as\u003Cstrong\u003E metronidazole (\u003C/strong\u003Eor tinidazole), to eliminate the parasite. Typical dosing is 250 to 500 mg 3 times a day for 5 to 10 days.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETrimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic used to treat bacterial infections. It is not effective against Giardia intestinalis, the parasite that causes Giardiasis, and would not be an appropriate treatment option. Sulfamethoxazole\u003Cstrong\u003E \u003C/strong\u003Eworks directly on the synthesis of folate inside microbial organism whereas trimethoprim is a direct competitor of the enzyme dihydrofolate reductase,\u0026nbsp;resulting in its inhibition, halting the production of tetrahydrofolate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParomomycin\u003C/strong\u003E is an antibiotic that is sometimes used to treat Giardiasis. However, it is not used as first-line treatment option therefore it would not be the most appropriate first-line treatment option for this case. It is poorly systemically absorbed and may be considered if giardiasis needs to be treated in a pregnant patient in her first trimester.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPenicillin \u003C/strong\u003Eis a beta-lactam drug used to manage and treat a wide range of infections. It inhibits the cross-linking of peptidoglycan in the bacterial cell wall. It is not effective against Giardia intestinalis, the parasite that causes Giardiasis, and hence not the correct answer.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAlbendazole \u003C/strong\u003Eis an anthelmintic used to treat parasitic infections. It is used in metronidazole refractory giardiasis and is not the first line treatment. It decreases adenosine triphosphate (ATP) production in parasites, causing energy depletion, immobilisation, and, finally, death.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Metronidazole is the treatment of choice for giardiasis."],"references":["Dunn N, Juergens AL. Giardiasis. [Updated 2022 May 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"20769"}},"question":{"data":{"ty